Hello.

I use AspNetCore2.0 in azure apps with Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.AzureAppServices 2.0.0

I want to output custom format log in Azure apps application logs and log streaming.
So that, I configure  AzureAppServicesDiagnosticsSettings.OutputTemplate.

Following my startup.cs 

```
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IHostingEnvironment env, ILoggerFactory loggerFactory)
        {

            loggerFactory.AddConsole(Configuration.GetSection("Logging"));
            loggerFactory.AddAzureWebAppDiagnostics(
                new AzureAppServicesDiagnosticsSettings
                {
                    OutputTemplate = "{Timestamp:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss zzz} [{Level}] {RequestId}-{SourceContext}: {Message}{NewLine}{Exception}"
                }
            );
```

but, Application log doesn't output above format.

And I find  that OutpuTemplate doens't use at [AzureAppServicesLoggerFactoryExtensions.cs](https://github.com/aspnet/Logging/blob/dev/src/Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.AzureAppServices/AzureAppServicesLoggerFactoryExtensions.cs) .

Please tell me AzureAppServicesDiagnosticsSettings.OutputTemplate is available ? 

Thanks.

Hi there,

Currently I can create a logger for a type using .CreateLogger<T>() extensions method.
This method calls .CreateLogger(Type) of the ILoggerFactory and wraps the result in Logger\<T>().

https://github.com/aspnet/Logging/blob/42ba2626b1a9e6327a43318e5888ed406e3f90da/src/Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Abstractions/LoggerFactoryExtensions.cs#L25

This wrapper (Logger\<T>) essentially makes it impossible to access wrapped logger directly, which from the end user is fine, but makes writing custom LoggerFactory/Logger bit harder for certain scenarios.

Would it be possible to change this slightly and, for example, introduce IGenericLoggerFactory with .CreateLogger\<T>() method? .CreateLogger<T>(this ILoggerFactory loggerFactory) extension method could then check if loggerFactory is IGenericLoggerFactory and use it to create generic wrapper or continue as before otherwise ?
```
public interface IGenericLoggerFactory
{
  public ILogger<T> CreateLogger<T>();
}

public static ILogger<T> CreateLogger<T>(this ILoggerFactory factory)
{
    if (factory == null)
    {
         throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(factory));
    }
    
    if(factory is IGenericLoggerFactory genericFactory)
    {
          return genericFactory.CreateLogger<T>();
    }
    else
    {
          return new Logger<T>(factory);
    }
}
```

Love the abstractions that this suite offers. However, my last company had a couple nice features in our logging library that I would see as beneficial to this library as well.

* `BeginContext` would be similar to `BeginScope` but would take a key and a potentially formattable value. This value would be carried though to each log message within the scope of the context `IDisposable`. This would avoid passing certain things around in the code. This is similar to #717  For instance:

Without `BeginContext`:
```
Guid correlationId = ...
using (logger.BeginScope("Process started {correlationId}", correlationId))
{
    MyMethodThatTracesLotsOfThings(correlationId, ...);
}

void MyMethodThatTracesLotsOfThings(Guid correlationId, ...)
{
    logger.LogInformation("We did something here with {correlationId}", correlationId); 
}
```

With `BeginContext`
```
Guid correlationId = ...
using (logger.BeginContext("correlationId", correlationId)
using (logger.BeginScope("Process started"))
{
    MyMethodThatTracesLotsOfThings(...);
}

void MyMethodThatTracesLotsOfThings(...)
{
    logger.LogInformation("We did something here"); 
}
```

The logger can use this for the tracing at will. `BeginScope` adds some of this facility, but is really tied to a single message.

* `TraceLevel.Always`. This would potentially be a breaking change with `TraceLevel`, but I sometimes want to unconditionally trace something. I know the logger implementations can still reject it, but I want to try from my application code to trace. `TraceLevel.None` should be `Int32.MinValue` and `TraceLevel.Always` should be `Int32.MaxValue`. 

Thoughts?

