What is the microsoft equivalent for this.

BeginScope does not write our these values when used with Serilog

EventID is marked as obsolete http://referencesource.microsoft.com/#System/services/monitoring/system/diagnosticts/EventLogEntry.cs#183
```
        /// <devdoc>
        ///    <para>
        ///       Gets the application-specific event indentifier of this entry.
        ///
        ///    </para>
        /// </devdoc>
        [
        MonitoringDescription(SR.LogEntryEventID),
        Obsolete("This property has been deprecated.  Please use System.Diagnostics.EventLogEntry.InstanceId instead.  http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=14202")
        ]
        public int EventID {
            get {
                // Apparently the top 2 bits of this number are not
                // always 0. Strip them so the number looks nice to the user.
                // The problem is, if the user were to want to call FormatMessage(),
                // they'd need these two bits.
                return IntFrom(dataBuf, bufOffset + FieldOffsets.EVENTID) & 0x3FFFFFFF;
            }
        }
```
and API immediatly throws when event ID is greater then 65535 http://referencesource.microsoft.com/#System/services/monitoring/system/diagnosticts/EventLogInternal.cs#1616
```
        public void WriteEntry(string message, EventLogEntryType type, int eventID, short category,
                               byte[] rawData) {
 
            if (eventID < 0 || eventID > ushort.MaxValue)
                throw new ArgumentException(SR.GetString(SR.EventID, eventID, 0, (int)ushort.MaxValue));
```
Luckily there is a replacement
http://referencesource.microsoft.com/#System/services/monitoring/system/diagnosticts/EventLog.cs#1432
```
        [ComVisible(false)]
        public void WriteEvent(EventInstance instance, byte[] data, params Object[] values) {
            m_underlyingEventLog.WriteEvent(instance, data, values);
        }
```

Note this issue has not been a problem with ASP.NET Core 1.x, but since 2.0 EF Core starts logging message with IDs like 2005000 for `The LINQ expression 'First()' could not be translated and will be evaluated locally.`

So this is pretty critical for anyone using 2.0

I'd like to get the original scopes in my exception handler as they usually contain important information for troubleshooting (e.g. the UserId). I've [read about a trick/hack](https://nblumhardt.com/2016/11/ilogger-beginscope/#comment-3012254418) that uses C# exception filters to execute the logging statement within the context of the location that throws the exception. Thanks to @nblumhardt and @skomis-mm for pointing this out.

However, it seems like this only works as long as there is no `TaskAwaiter` involved:

```csharp
public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        new WebHostBuilder()
            .UseKestrel()
            .UseContentRoot(Directory.GetCurrentDirectory())
            .ConfigureLogging(logging =>
            {
                logging.AddConsole(options => options.IncludeScopes = true);
                logging.AddFilter("Microsoft", LogLevel.Warning);
            })
            .Configure(app =>
            {
                var logger = app.ApplicationServices.GetRequiredService<ILogger<Program>>();

                app.Map("/sync", subApp =>
                {
                    // Exception handler
                    subApp.Use(async (context, next) =>
                    {
                        try
                        {
                            await next();
                        }
                        catch (Exception ex) when (LogError(logger, ex))
                        {
                        }
                    });
                    // Logic
                    subApp.Run((context) =>
                    {
                        using (logger.BeginScope("UserId:100"))
                        {
                            throw new InvalidOperationException("Something went wrong");
                        }
                    });
                });

                app.Map("/async", subApp =>
                {
                    // Exception handler
                    subApp.Use(async (context, next) =>
                    {
                        try
                        {
                            await next();
                        }
                        catch (Exception ex) when (LogError(logger, ex))
                        {
                        }
                    });
                    // Logic
                    subApp.Run(async (context) =>
                    {
                        using (logger.BeginScope("UserId:100"))
                        {
                            await Task.Delay(100); // Force TaskAwaiter
                            throw new InvalidOperationException("Something went wrong");
                        }
                    });
                });
            })
            .Build()
            .Run();
    }

    public static bool LogError(ILogger logger, Exception ex)
    {
        logger.LogError(ex, "Unhandled exception");
        return true;
    }
}
```

A request to "/sync" outputs the "UserId:100" scope for the "LogError"-call:
```
fail: HostingLogging.Program[0]
      => ConnectionId:0HL6NFB0MJHO8 => RequestId:0HL6NFB0MJHO8:00000001 RequestPath: => UserId:100
      Unhandled exception
System.InvalidOperationException: Something went wrong
   at HostingLogging.Program.<>c__DisplayClass0_0.<Main>b__5(HttpContext context) in C:\src\tmp\HostingLogging\Program.cs:line 51
   at HostingLogging.Program.<>c__DisplayClass0_0.<<Main>b__4>d.MoveNext() in C:\src\tmp\HostingLogging\Program.cs:line 40
```
A request to "/async" does NOT output the "UserId:100" scope for the "LogError"-call:
```
fail: HostingLogging.Program[0]
      => ConnectionId:0HL6NFB0MJHO8 => RequestId:0HL6NFB0MJHO8:00000002 RequestPath:
      Unhandled exception
System.InvalidOperationException: Something went wrong
   at HostingLogging.Program.<>c__DisplayClass0_0.<<Main>b__8>d.MoveNext() in C:\src\tmp\HostingLogging\Program.cs:line 75
--- End of stack trace from previous location where exception was thrown ---
   at System.Runtime.ExceptionServices.ExceptionDispatchInfo.Throw()
   at System.Runtime.CompilerServices.TaskAwaiter.HandleNonSuccessAndDebuggerNotification(Task task)
   at HostingLogging.Program.<>c__DisplayClass0_0.<<Main>b__7>d.MoveNext() in C:\src\tmp\HostingLogging\Program.cs:line 63
```
As this feels like a hack anyway, I guess there's no way to get the scopes in async-scenarios, right?

I know that I could catch exceptions within each scope but this isn't really an option IMO as this would result in multiple log entries (one for each scope).

Are there any alternatives for what I want or would it be worth discussing possible solutions?

`LogError` and `LogCritical` should send the logmessages to `Console.Error`-stream. Right now the output is just sent to `Console.Out`.

### Minimal repro steps

```c#
namespace Foo
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            var loggerFactory = new LoggerFactory()
                .AddConsole();

            var logger = loggerFactory.CreateLogger<Program>();

            logger.LogInformation("Test");
            logger.LogError("Error");

            // Make sure the consumer on the write-side can drain the queue
            Thread.Sleep(500);
        }
    }
}
```

`dotnet foo.dll > out.txt 2> err.txt`

### Expected result
_err.txt_ should contain the logged error messaged. Critical messages, although not shown in the sample above, should also get sent to stderr.

### Actual result
All logged messages are sent to the standard output stream.

Hello, after upgrade to version 2.0.0-preview2 LoggerFactory filtering is broken and there is no method AddFilter anymore. Can you suggest how to filter built in event sources in new version or did i miss something?
Here is my ConfigureServices part:
```var loggerFactory = new LoggerFactory();
            loggerFactory.AddFilter(new Dictionary<string, LogLevel>
            {
                { "Microsoft", LogLevel.Warning },
                { "System", LogLevel.Error },
                { "Engine", LogLevel.Debug }
            });
            loggerFactory.AddLog4Net();

These are the methods as they are defined today 
```
        public static IWebHostBuilder ConfigureLogging(this IWebHostBuilder hostBuilder, Action<ILoggingBuilder> configureLogging);

        public static IWebHostBuilder ConfigureLogging(this IWebHostBuilder hostBuilder, Action<WebHostBuilderContext, ILoggingBuilder> configureLogging);
```

Try this out, start typing out something like
```
WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args) .ConfigureLogging(b => 
{
    b.    
});
```

The completions after the `b.` are for the `Action<WebHostBuilderContext, ILoggingBuilder>` overload even though we only have one parameter. Basically type inference for the lambda won't do the right thing unless we have exactly correct code inside the lambda.

Since so much of the `ILoggingBuilder` API is extensions, this is a royal pain since intellisense won't show you what's going on.

My guess is that `UseDefaultServiceProvider` also behaves similarly.

## Issue
ConsoleLogger sometimes truncates latter parts of logs
## Cause
I think the issue may be related to the addition of `_outputTask.Wait(1500)` to `ConsoleLoggerProcessor.Dispose()`:
```csharp
// ConsoleLoggerProcessor.cs
public void Dispose()
{
    _messageQueue.CompleteAdding();

    try
    {
        _outputTask.Wait(1500); // with timeout in-case Console is locked by user input
    }
    catch (TaskCanceledException) { }
    catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1 && ex.InnerExceptions[0] is 
    TaskCanceledException) { }
}
```
If a queue takes longer than 1500ms to clear, logs will be truncated.
## Reproduction
[Repo](https://github.com/JeremyTCD/ConsoleLoggerOutput/tree/master). This is a simple reproduction of the issue. To use, build the solution and debug OutputCapturer. Debug output will reflect that some messages from OutputGenerator get truncated. 
## Additional Notes
I think it would be a good idea to guarantee that all log messages are always written (like before Console.WriteLine was moved out of the critical path). Otherwise, additional documentation to warn that logs may be truncated in certain scenarios should probably be added.

